{"title_page": "Extraterrestrial real estate", "text_new": " Vector. Vector owns the moon.\n[[File:Moon merged small.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The Moon as seen by an observer from Earth. It is claimed as private property by several individuals.<ref name=CNN_moonown>{{cite web | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/TECH/space/05/19/moon.land/index.html | title =  Who owns the moon? It's 'complicated,' say experts | year = 2008 | publisher = [[CNN]]}}</ref><ref name=newser_moon>{{cite web | url = http://www.newser.com/story/167265/this-man-claims-he-owns-the-moon.html | title = This Man Claims He Owns the Moon | publisher = Newser| year = 2013}}</ref>]]\n'''Extraterrestrial real estate''' refers to claims of land ownership on other [[planet]]s or [[natural satellite]]s or parts of [[outer space|space]] by certain organizations, individuals, and scam artists. Such claims are not recognized by any authority, and have no legal standing.<ref name=whoowns>{{cite book\n| title=Who Owns the Moon?: Extraterrestrial Aspects of Land and Mineral Resources Ownershipwork\n| author=Virgiliu G Pop\n| authorlink=Virgiliu Pop\n| publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]\n| year=2009\n| pages=2\u20133\n| isbn=978-1402091346}}</ref> Nevertheless, some private individuals and organizations have claimed ownership of celestial bodies, such as the Moon, and are actively involved in \"selling\" parts of them through certificates of ownership termed \"Lunar deeds\",<ref name=whoowns/> \"Martian deeds\" or similar.\n\n== History ==\nThe topic of real estate on celestial objects has been present since the 1890s. Dean Lindsay made claims for all extraterrestrial objects on June 15, 1936.  The public sent offers to buy objects from him as well.<ref name=whoowns/>\n\n==Legal issues==\n{{International ownership conventions}}\n\nThe [[United Nations]] sponsored 1967 \"[[Outer Space Treaty]]\" established all of outer space as an international commons by describing it as the \"province of all mankind\" and forbidding all the [[nation state|nations]] from claiming territorial sovereignty.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.unoosa.org/pdf/publications/STSPACE11E.pdf\n| title = United Nations Treaties And Principles On Outer Space\n| year=2002\n| publisher = United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs\n| accessdate = 2013-06-04}}</ref> Article VI vests the responsibility for activities in space to States Parties, regardless of whether they are carried out by governments or non-governmental entities. The Outer Space Treaty of 1967 had been ratified by 102 countries by 2013,<ref name=\"treatystatus\">{{cite web\n| url=http://www.oosa.unvienna.org/oosa/en/SpaceLaw/treatystatus/index.html\n| title=Status of International Agreements relating to Activities in Outer Space\n| date=2013-01-01\n| publisher=[[UNOOSA|United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> including all the major space-faring nations. It has also been signed but not yet ratified by 26 other nations.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.unoosa.org/pdf/publications/ST_SPACE_11_Add1_Rev2E.pdf\n| title = Status of international agreements relating to activities in outer space as at 1 January 2005\n| date = February 2005\n| publisher = United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs\n| accessdate = 2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent treaty document, the international [[Moon Treaty]]\u2014finalised in 1979 (just five countries had ratified it by 1984, but five countries was sufficient for it to be considered officially \"in force\")\u2014went further and forbade private ownership of extraterrestrial real estate.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://lunar.arc.nasa.gov/results/ice/moon.htm\n |title       = Moon Treaty\n |publisher   = [[NASA Ames Research Center]]\n |date        = 2001-08-31\n |accessdate  = 2013-06-04\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130606192246/http://lunar.arc.nasa.gov/results/ice/moon.htm\n |archivedate = 2013-06-06\n}} {{dead link|date=August 2018}}</ref> This agreement has not been widely ratified.<ref name=\"treatystatus\"/><ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.unoosa.org/oosa/SpaceLaw/moon.html\n| title=Agreement Governing the Activities of States on the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies\n| publisher=United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> with only 18 countries having ratified it by 2018.<ref name=untdb201808>\n{{cite web |url=http://disarmament.un.org/treaties/t/moon |title=Agreement Governing the Activities of States on the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies |publisher=[[United Nations Office for Disarmament Affairs]] |accessdate=2018-08-19}}</ref>\n\nSeveral individuals and private organizations claimed ownership of the moon and other extraterrestrial bodies, but no such claims have yet been recognized. A white paper by the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] suggested legislation whereby the US would recognize claims made by private entities, American and others, which meet certain conditions regarding habitation and transportation.<ref name=tsr20120409>\n{{cite web |url = http://www.thespacereview.com/article/2058/1 |title = Staking a claim on the Moon |last=Foust|first=Jeff |work=The Space Review |date=9 April 2012 |access-date=20 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Private purchase schemes==\nA number of individuals and organizations offer schemes or plans claiming to allow people to purchase portions of the [[Moon]] or other celestial bodies. Though the details of some of the schemes' legal arguments vary, one goes so far as to state that although the [[Outer Space Treaty]], which entered force in 1967, forbids countries from claiming celestial bodies, there is no such provision forbidding private individuals from doing so. However, Article VI of this treaty states \"The activities of non-governmental entities in outer space, including the moon and other celestial bodies, shall require authorization and continuing supervision by the appropriate State Party to the Treaty.\" Thus, while it does not explicitly prohibit such schemes, the treaty does require they be authorized by the schemers' government.\n\nThe [[short story]] ''[[The Man Who Sold the Moon]]'' by [[Robert A. Heinlein]], which was written in 1949, offers a portrayal regarding such plans or schemes, and created the concept of a Lunar Republic. Heinlein's ''[[Stranger in a Strange Land]]'' also makes reference to a space law case called the ''Larkin Decision''.\n\n===Geostationary orbits{{anchor|Bogota Declaration}}===\nA space ownership issue of current practical importance is the allocation of slots for satellites in [[geostationary orbit]]. This is managed by the [[International Telecommunication Union]]. The 1976 Declaration of the First Meeting of Equatorial Countries, also known as the '''Bogot\u00e1 Declaration''', signed by several countries located on the Earth's [[equator]], attempted to assert sovereignty over those portions of the geostationary orbit that continuously lie over the signatory nation's territory.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.jaxa.jp/library/space_law/chapter_2/2-2-1-2_e.html\n| title=Text of Declaration of the First Meeting of Equatorial Countries\n| date=2007-01-23\n| publisher=[[Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> These claims did not receive wider international support or recognition and were subsequently largely abandoned.\n\n==Notable claims==\nChilean lawyer [[Jenaro Gajardo Vera]] became famous for his 1953 claim of ownership of the [[Moon]].<ref name=whoowns>{{cite book\n| title=Who Owns the Moon?: Extraterrestrial Aspects of Land and Mineral Resources Ownershipwork\n| author=Virgiliu G Pop\n| authorlink=Virgiliu Pop\n| publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]\n| year=2009\n| pages=2\u20133\n| isbn=978-1402091346}}</ref>\n\nMartin Juergens from Germany claims that the Moon has belonged to his family since July 15, 1756, when the Prussian king Frederick the Great presented it to his ancestor Aul Juergens as a symbolic gesture of gratitude for services rendered, and decreed that it should pass to the youngest born son.<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://www.parascope.com/articles/1196/moonw.htm\n| title=The Moon Is Mine\n| last=Tull\n| first=D.\n| year=1996\n| work=Parascope\n| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313201737/http://parascope.com/articles/1196/moonw.htm\n| archivedate=March 13, 2016| url-status=dead\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nA. Dean Lindsay made claims for all extraterrestrial objects on June 15, 1936, and sent a letter to Pittsburgh Notary Public along with a deed and money for establishment of the property. The public sent offers to buy objects from him as well.<ref name=\"whoowns\"/>  He had previously made claims on the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pop|first1=Virgiliu|title=Unreal Estate - The Men who Sold the Moon|date=2006|publisher=Exposure Publishing|isbn=1846850959|page=17|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GllWkewypw4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\n[[James T. Mangan]] (1896\u20131970) was a famous eccentric, public relations man and best-selling author on self-help topics who publicly claimed ownership of [[outer space]] in 1948. Mangan founded what he called the ''[[Nation of Celestial Space]]'' and registered it with the Recorder of Deeds and Titles of [[Cook County, Illinois]], on January 1, 1949.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://blog.modernmechanix.com/chicago-man-stakes-claim-to-outer-space/\n| title=Chicago Man Stakes Claim to Outer Space (May, 1949)\n| date=2008-07-10\n| work=[[Science Illustrated]]\n| publisher=blog.modernmechanix.com\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nRobert R. Coles, former chairman of New York's [[Hayden Planetarium]], started \"the interplanetary Development Corporation\"<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/U1094418/robert-r-coles-pointing-to-moon-map\n| title=Robert R. Coles Pointing to Moon Map\n| date=1955-11-17\n| publisher=[[Branded Entertainment Network|Corbis]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> and sold lots on the moon for one dollar per acre ($2.50/ha).<ref>W N White Jr., 1985, 'Real Property Rights in Outer Space', Unpublished academic version. Footnote 79 at p.41, quoting a Newsweek report of December the 5th, 1955, p. 31. The quotation of the primary source is inexact.</ref>\n\nDennis Hope, an [[United States|American]] [[entrepreneur]], sells extraterrestrial real estate.<ref name=geo>{{cite web\n| url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2009/07/090717-who-owns-moon-real-estate.html\n| title=Who Owns the Moon? The Galactic Government vs. The UN\n| first=Victoria\n| last=Jaggard\n| date=2009-07-17\n| publisher=[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic News]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> In 1980, he started his own business, the Lunar Embassy Commission.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.lunarembassy.com/\n| title=Lunar Embassy - World Headquarters\n| date=2006-07-17\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> As of 2009 Hope claimed to have sold 2.5M {{convert|1|acre|ha m2|adj=on}} plots on the Moon, for around US$20 per acre ($50/ha). He allocates land to be sold by closing his eyes and randomly pointing to a map of the Moon. He claims two former US presidents as customers, stating [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] had aides purchase the plots on the moon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Meet the Man Who Owns the Moon|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/03/25/meet-the-man-who-owns-the-moon|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=USNews|date=25 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=DENNIS M. HOPE HAS OWNED THE MOON SINCE 1980 BECAUSE HE SAYS SO|url=https://www.vice.com/read/ive-owned-the-moon-since-1980|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=VICE|date=11 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Adam Ismail, Mustafa Khalil and Abdullah al-Umari, three men from Yemen, sued [[NASA]] for invading Mars. They claim that they \"inherited the planet from our ancestors 3,000 years ago\", before [[Muhammad]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://edition.cnn.com/TECH/9707/24/yemen.mars/\n| title=3 Yemenis sue NASA for trespassing on Mars\n| work=[[CNN]]\n| date=1997-07-24\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> They based their argument on mythologies of the [[Sabaean language|Himyaritic]] and [[Sabaeans|Sabaean]] civilizations that existed several thousand years B.C.<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/despatches/67814.stm\n| title=Yemenis claim Mars\n| work=BBC News\n| date=1998-03-22\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nGregory W. Nemitz claimed ownership of Asteroid [[433 Eros]], on which [[NEAR Shoemaker]] landed in 2001. His company, called \"Orbital Development\",<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.orbdev.com/\n| title=Orbital Development\n| date=August 2007\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> issued NASA an invoice of $20 for parking the spacecraft at the asteroid. NASA declined to pay, citing the lack of legal standing.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.erosproject.com/legal.html\n| title=The Eros Project: Legal Actions\n| date=2004-03-08\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Garriott]], computer game designer and astronaut's son, legitimately purchased the [[Lunokhod 2]] lunar lander from the Russian Space Agency. Since then he jokingly claimed the rest of the Moon in the name of his gaming character, [[Lord British]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://demiurg.net/games/lb/\n| title= Lord British, we hardly knew ye\n| first=Cindy\n| last=Yans\n| date=2001-04-13\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Georgism]] \n*[[Land claim]]\n*[[Star designation#Sale of star names by non-scientific entities|Sale of star names]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.permanent.com/archimedes/LawLibrary.html \"Library of space law\"]\n*[http://www.unoosa.org/oosa/en/SpaceLaw/outerspt.html \"Treaty on Principles Governing the Activities of States in the Exploration and Use of Outer Space, Including the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies\"]\n*[http://www.asi.org/adb/j/02/legal-roadblocks.html Moon Treaty]\n\n{{Real estate}}\n{{Scams and confidence tricks}}\n\n[[Category:Space law]]\n[[Category:Exploration of the Moon]]\n[[Category:Real estate]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Moon merged small.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The Moon as seen by an observer from Earth. It is claimed as private property by several individuals.<ref name=CNN_moonown>{{cite web | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/TECH/space/05/19/moon.land/index.html | title =  Who owns the moon? It's 'complicated,' say experts | year = 2008 | publisher = [[CNN]]}}</ref><ref name=newser_moon>{{cite web | url = http://www.newser.com/story/167265/this-man-claims-he-owns-the-moon.html | title = This Man Claims He Owns the Moon | publisher = Newser| year = 2013}}</ref>]]\n'''Extraterrestrial real estate''' refers to claims of land ownership on other [[planet]]s or [[natural satellite]]s or parts of [[outer space|space]] by certain organizations, individuals, and scam artists. Such claims are not recognized by any authority, and have no legal standing.<ref name=whoowns>{{cite book\n| title=Who Owns the Moon?: Extraterrestrial Aspects of Land and Mineral Resources Ownershipwork\n| author=Virgiliu G Pop\n| authorlink=Virgiliu Pop\n| publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]\n| year=2009\n| pages=2\u20133\n| isbn=978-1402091346}}</ref> Nevertheless, some private individuals and organizations have claimed ownership of celestial bodies, such as the Moon, and are actively involved in \"selling\" parts of them through certificates of ownership termed \"Lunar deeds\",<ref name=whoowns/> \"Martian deeds\" or similar.\n\n== History ==\nThe topic of real estate on celestial objects has been present since the 1890s. Dean Lindsay made claims for all extraterrestrial objects on June 15, 1936.  The public sent offers to buy objects from him as well.<ref name=whoowns/>\n\n==Legal issues==\n{{International ownership conventions}}\n\nThe [[United Nations]] sponsored 1967 \"[[Outer Space Treaty]]\" established all of outer space as an international commons by describing it as the \"province of all mankind\" and forbidding all the [[nation state|nations]] from claiming territorial sovereignty.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.unoosa.org/pdf/publications/STSPACE11E.pdf\n| title = United Nations Treaties And Principles On Outer Space\n| year=2002\n| publisher = United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs\n| accessdate = 2013-06-04}}</ref> Article VI vests the responsibility for activities in space to States Parties, regardless of whether they are carried out by governments or non-governmental entities. The Outer Space Treaty of 1967 had been ratified by 102 countries by 2013,<ref name=\"treatystatus\">{{cite web\n| url=http://www.oosa.unvienna.org/oosa/en/SpaceLaw/treatystatus/index.html\n| title=Status of International Agreements relating to Activities in Outer Space\n| date=2013-01-01\n| publisher=[[UNOOSA|United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> including all the major space-faring nations. It has also been signed but not yet ratified by 26 other nations.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.unoosa.org/pdf/publications/ST_SPACE_11_Add1_Rev2E.pdf\n| title = Status of international agreements relating to activities in outer space as at 1 January 2005\n| date = February 2005\n| publisher = United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs\n| accessdate = 2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent treaty document, the international [[Moon Treaty]]\u2014finalised in 1979 (just five countries had ratified it by 1984, but five countries was sufficient for it to be considered officially \"in force\")\u2014went further and forbade private ownership of extraterrestrial real estate.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://lunar.arc.nasa.gov/results/ice/moon.htm\n |title       = Moon Treaty\n |publisher   = [[NASA Ames Research Center]]\n |date        = 2001-08-31\n |accessdate  = 2013-06-04\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130606192246/http://lunar.arc.nasa.gov/results/ice/moon.htm\n |archivedate = 2013-06-06\n}} {{dead link|date=August 2018}}</ref> This agreement has not been widely ratified.<ref name=\"treatystatus\"/><ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.unoosa.org/oosa/SpaceLaw/moon.html\n| title=Agreement Governing the Activities of States on the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies\n| publisher=United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> with only 18 countries having ratified it by 2018.<ref name=untdb201808>\n{{cite web |url=http://disarmament.un.org/treaties/t/moon |title=Agreement Governing the Activities of States on the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies |publisher=[[United Nations Office for Disarmament Affairs]] |accessdate=2018-08-19}}</ref>\n\nSeveral individuals and private organizations claimed ownership of the moon and other extraterrestrial bodies, but no such claims have yet been recognized. A white paper by the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]] suggested legislation whereby the US would recognize claims made by private entities, American and others, which meet certain conditions regarding habitation and transportation.<ref name=tsr20120409>\n{{cite web |url = http://www.thespacereview.com/article/2058/1 |title = Staking a claim on the Moon |last=Foust|first=Jeff |work=The Space Review |date=9 April 2012 |access-date=20 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Private purchase schemes==\nA number of individuals and organizations offer schemes or plans claiming to allow people to purchase portions of the [[Moon]] or other celestial bodies. Though the details of some of the schemes' legal arguments vary, one goes so far as to state that although the [[Outer Space Treaty]], which entered force in 1967, forbids countries from claiming celestial bodies, there is no such provision forbidding private individuals from doing so. However, Article VI of this treaty states \"The activities of non-governmental entities in outer space, including the moon and other celestial bodies, shall require authorization and continuing supervision by the appropriate State Party to the Treaty.\" Thus, while it does not explicitly prohibit such schemes, the treaty does require they be authorized by the schemers' government.\n\nThe [[short story]] ''[[The Man Who Sold the Moon]]'' by [[Robert A. Heinlein]], which was written in 1949, offers a portrayal regarding such plans or schemes, and created the concept of a Lunar Republic. Heinlein's ''[[Stranger in a Strange Land]]'' also makes reference to a space law case called the ''Larkin Decision''.\n\n===Geostationary orbits{{anchor|Bogota Declaration}}===\nA space ownership issue of current practical importance is the allocation of slots for satellites in [[geostationary orbit]]. This is managed by the [[International Telecommunication Union]]. The 1976 Declaration of the First Meeting of Equatorial Countries, also known as the '''Bogot\u00e1 Declaration''', signed by several countries located on the Earth's [[equator]], attempted to assert sovereignty over those portions of the geostationary orbit that continuously lie over the signatory nation's territory.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.jaxa.jp/library/space_law/chapter_2/2-2-1-2_e.html\n| title=Text of Declaration of the First Meeting of Equatorial Countries\n| date=2007-01-23\n| publisher=[[Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> These claims did not receive wider international support or recognition and were subsequently largely abandoned.\n\n==Notable claims==\nChilean lawyer [[Jenaro Gajardo Vera]] became famous for his 1953 claim of ownership of the [[Moon]].<ref name=whoowns>{{cite book\n| title=Who Owns the Moon?: Extraterrestrial Aspects of Land and Mineral Resources Ownershipwork\n| author=Virgiliu G Pop\n| authorlink=Virgiliu Pop\n| publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]\n| year=2009\n| pages=2\u20133\n| isbn=978-1402091346}}</ref>\n\nMartin Juergens from Germany claims that the Moon has belonged to his family since July 15, 1756, when the Prussian king Frederick the Great presented it to his ancestor Aul Juergens as a symbolic gesture of gratitude for services rendered, and decreed that it should pass to the youngest born son.<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://www.parascope.com/articles/1196/moonw.htm\n| title=The Moon Is Mine\n| last=Tull\n| first=D.\n| year=1996\n| work=Parascope\n| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313201737/http://parascope.com/articles/1196/moonw.htm\n| archivedate=March 13, 2016| url-status=dead\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nA. Dean Lindsay made claims for all extraterrestrial objects on June 15, 1936, and sent a letter to Pittsburgh Notary Public along with a deed and money for establishment of the property. The public sent offers to buy objects from him as well.<ref name=\"whoowns\"/>  He had previously made claims on the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pop|first1=Virgiliu|title=Unreal Estate - The Men who Sold the Moon|date=2006|publisher=Exposure Publishing|isbn=1846850959|page=17|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GllWkewypw4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>\n\n[[James T. Mangan]] (1896\u20131970) was a famous eccentric, public relations man and best-selling author on self-help topics who publicly claimed ownership of [[outer space]] in 1948. Mangan founded what he called the ''[[Nation of Celestial Space]]'' and registered it with the Recorder of Deeds and Titles of [[Cook County, Illinois]], on January 1, 1949.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://blog.modernmechanix.com/chicago-man-stakes-claim-to-outer-space/\n| title=Chicago Man Stakes Claim to Outer Space (May, 1949)\n| date=2008-07-10\n| work=[[Science Illustrated]]\n| publisher=blog.modernmechanix.com\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nRobert R. Coles, former chairman of New York's [[Hayden Planetarium]], started \"the interplanetary Development Corporation\"<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.corbisimages.com/stock-photo/rights-managed/U1094418/robert-r-coles-pointing-to-moon-map\n| title=Robert R. Coles Pointing to Moon Map\n| date=1955-11-17\n| publisher=[[Branded Entertainment Network|Corbis]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> and sold lots on the moon for one dollar per acre ($2.50/ha).<ref>W N White Jr., 1985, 'Real Property Rights in Outer Space', Unpublished academic version. Footnote 79 at p.41, quoting a Newsweek report of December the 5th, 1955, p. 31. The quotation of the primary source is inexact.</ref>\n\nDennis Hope, an [[United States|American]] [[entrepreneur]], sells extraterrestrial real estate.<ref name=geo>{{cite web\n| url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2009/07/090717-who-owns-moon-real-estate.html\n| title=Who Owns the Moon? The Galactic Government vs. The UN\n| first=Victoria\n| last=Jaggard\n| date=2009-07-17\n| publisher=[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic News]]\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> In 1980, he started his own business, the Lunar Embassy Commission.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.lunarembassy.com/\n| title=Lunar Embassy - World Headquarters\n| date=2006-07-17\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> As of 2009 Hope claimed to have sold 2.5M {{convert|1|acre|ha m2|adj=on}} plots on the Moon, for around US$20 per acre ($50/ha). He allocates land to be sold by closing his eyes and randomly pointing to a map of the Moon. He claims two former US presidents as customers, stating [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] had aides purchase the plots on the moon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Meet the Man Who Owns the Moon|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/03/25/meet-the-man-who-owns-the-moon|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=USNews|date=25 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=DENNIS M. HOPE HAS OWNED THE MOON SINCE 1980 BECAUSE HE SAYS SO|url=https://www.vice.com/read/ive-owned-the-moon-since-1980|accessdate=5 April 2014|newspaper=VICE|date=11 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Adam Ismail, Mustafa Khalil and Abdullah al-Umari, three men from Yemen, sued [[NASA]] for invading Mars. They claim that they \"inherited the planet from our ancestors 3,000 years ago\", before [[Muhammad]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://edition.cnn.com/TECH/9707/24/yemen.mars/\n| title=3 Yemenis sue NASA for trespassing on Mars\n| work=[[CNN]]\n| date=1997-07-24\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> They based their argument on mythologies of the [[Sabaean language|Himyaritic]] and [[Sabaeans|Sabaean]] civilizations that existed several thousand years B.C.<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/despatches/67814.stm\n| title=Yemenis claim Mars\n| work=BBC News\n| date=1998-03-22\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\nGregory W. Nemitz claimed ownership of Asteroid [[433 Eros]], on which [[NEAR Shoemaker]] landed in 2001. His company, called \"Orbital Development\",<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.orbdev.com/\n| title=Orbital Development\n| date=August 2007\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> issued NASA an invoice of $20 for parking the spacecraft at the asteroid. NASA declined to pay, citing the lack of legal standing.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.erosproject.com/legal.html\n| title=The Eros Project: Legal Actions\n| date=2004-03-08\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Garriott]], computer game designer and astronaut's son, legitimately purchased the [[Lunokhod 2]] lunar lander from the Russian Space Agency. Since then he jokingly claimed the rest of the Moon in the name of his gaming character, [[Lord British]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://demiurg.net/games/lb/\n| title= Lord British, we hardly knew ye\n| first=Cindy\n| last=Yans\n| date=2001-04-13\n| accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Georgism]] \n*[[Land claim]]\n*[[Star designation#Sale of star names by non-scientific entities|Sale of star names]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.permanent.com/archimedes/LawLibrary.html \"Library of space law\"]\n*[http://www.unoosa.org/oosa/en/SpaceLaw/outerspt.html \"Treaty on Principles Governing the Activities of States in the Exploration and Use of Outer Space, Including the Moon and Other Celestial Bodies\"]\n*[http://www.asi.org/adb/j/02/legal-roadblocks.html Moon Treaty]\n\n{{Real estate}}\n{{Scams and confidence tricks}}\n\n[[Category:Space law]]\n[[Category:Exploration of the Moon]]\n[[Category:Real estate]]\n", "name_user": "2001:569:7651:e800:7105:93a6:35e2:887d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extraterrestrial_real_estate"}
{"title_page": "The Man of the Woods Tour", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{short description|2018 Justin Timberlake tour}}\n{{Infobox concert\n|concert_tour_name=The Man of the Woods Tour\n|image=The Man of the Woods Tour.png\n|image_size=220px\n|border=yes\n|artist=[[Justin Timberlake]]\n|album=''[[Man of the Woods]]''\n|start_date={{Start date|2018|03|13}}\n|end_date={{End date|2019|04|13}}\n|number_of_legs=3\n|number_of_shows=115\n|attendance=1.75 million<ref name=\"2019 gross\"/>\n|gross=$226.3 million<ref name=\"2019 gross\"/>\n|last_tour=[[The 20/20 Experience World Tour]]<br />(2013\u201315)\n|this_tour='''The Man of the Woods Tour'''<br />(2018\u201319)\n}}\n\n'''The Man of the Woods Tour''' was the sixth concert tour by American singer-songwriter [[Justin Timberlake]]. Launched in support of his fifth studio album, ''[[Man of the Woods]]'' (2018), the tour began on March 13, 2018 in [[Toronto]] and concluded on April 13, 2019 in [[Uncasville]]. ''The Man of the Woods Tour'' was the sixth-highest-grossing tour of 2018. During its thirteen-month run from March 2018 to April 2019, ''The Man of the Woods Tour'' sold over 1.75&nbsp;million tickets and grossed a total of over $226.3&nbsp;million from 115 shows, making it Timberlake's second most successful tour to date behind only [[The 20/20 Experience World Tour]], which grossed over $231.6&nbsp;million from 134 shows, though Timberlake's per-night basis for ''The Man of the Woods Tour'' had a higher average at $1.96&nbsp;million per-show than that of ''The 20/20 Experience World Tour'', which averaged $1.81&nbsp;million per-show.<ref name=\"2019 gross\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8507576/justin-timberlake-earns-226-million-man-of-the-woods-tour/|title=Justin Timberlake Man of the Woods Tour|last=Eric|first=Frankenberg |date=April 17, 2019 |work=Billboard |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe tour was first announced in January 2018, and due to demand additional dates were released soon after. On February 5, 2018, the day following Timberlake's [[Super Bowl LII]] [[Super Bowl LII halftime show|halftime show]], Timberlake announced European tour dates, as well as second and third North American tour dates. Timberlake toured Europe after the first North American leg, then toured North America again starting in the fall. The third North American leg began in January 2019.<ref name=\"Man of the Woods Tour Dates\">{{cite web|title=Bringing Sexy Back! Justin Timberlake Announces The Man of the Woods Tour After Releasing New Single \u2014 Get the Dates|url=http://people.com/music/justin-timberlake-man-of-the-woods-tour-dates/|website=People|publisher=Time Inc.|authors=Nicole Sands, Sarah Michaud|accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Europe\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/justin-timberlake-announces-scottish-tour-11973346|title=Justin Timberlake announces Scottish tour date after Super Bowl performance|last=Harding|first=Laura|date=February 5, 2018|work=dailyrecord}}</ref><ref name=\"Timberlake Extends\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/after-super-bowl-set-justin-timberlake-extends-man-of-the-woods-tour-into-2019-1202687265/|title=After Super Bowl Set, Justin Timberlake Extends 'Man of the Woods' Tour Into 2019|work=Variety|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=February 5, 2018}}</ref> \nFrom November to December 2018, due to Timberlake suffering from bruised vocal cords, he was forced to postpone all remaining 2018 tour dates, resulting in the tour concluding in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/justin-timberlake-postpones-all-remaining-2018-shows-due-to-bruised-vocal-cords-115194|title=Justin Timberlake Postpones All Remaining 2018 Shows|website=Entertainment Tonight}}</ref>\n\n==Show==\nDuring a portion of the concert, Timberlake and his band the \"Tennessee Kids\" sing around a campfire. The \"Stage Bar\" VIP Experience on the tour includes a bar near the center stage, and a drink ticket. A disco dance floor is near the stage, where Timberlake performs \"[[Rock Your Body]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8247016/justin-timberlake-man-of-the-woods-opening-night-highlights|title=Five Highlights From Justin Timberlake's Opening Night of the Man of the Woods Tour|work=billboard}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The design is based off the floodplain maps of the [[Mississippi River]] as it runs through Memphis, which is his hometown. We wanted it to be a really organic, never-before-seen type stage that ran through the entire arena and engaged all the fans so everyone could have a front row seat.| Nick Whitehouse, creative producer/lighting designer for the tour.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.livedesignonline.com/concerts/key-moments-justin-timberlakes-man-woods-tour/gallery?slide=1 |title=Key Moments From Justin Timberlake's Man Of The Woods Tour |last=Perkins |first=Meghan |date=January 11, 2019 |work=[[Live Design]] |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n==Commercial performance==\nIn May 2018, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' reported grosses totalling $36.6&nbsp;million from the first five weeks, with 255,780 attendees at 16 shows, thus reaching number one on the magazine's weekly ranking Hot Tours. The magazine expects the tour to reach a total of $275&nbsp;million and 2&nbsp;million attendees by the time it concludes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8452059/justin-timberlake-man-of-the-woods-tour-37-million-earned |title=Justin Timberlake's Man of the Woods Tour: $37 Million Earned, And Counting |last=Allen |first=Bob |date=May 3, 2018 |work=Billboard |access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Timberlake's sold-out Orlando concert on May 14 was the highest-grossing, single-day concert in [[Amway Center]] history with $2,387,112 and 17,839 attendees.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/os-et-justin-timberlake-amway-center-record-20180515-story.html|title=Amway Center makes history with Justin Timberlake concert|work=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref>\n\nTimberlake's September 20 night concert at [[Rupp Arena]] grossed $2&nbsp;million, making it the highest-grossing one-night concert in the arena's history, besting the previous record set by the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]], which grossed $1.8&nbsp;million in June 2015.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.kentucky.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/article218722485.html |title=Justin Timberlake\u2019s Rupp concert sets one-night record. But he\u2019s about to be beat by a Beatle. |last=Musgrave |first=Beth |date=September 20, 2018 |work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis January 26, 2019 concert at the [[Chesapeake Energy Arena]] set a new record for highest-grossing show in [[Oklahoma City]]'s history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newson6.com/story/39870479/justin-timberlakes-man-of-the-woods-tour-sets-okc-record |title=Justin Timberlake's 'Man Of The Woods' Tour Sets OKC Record |date=January 29, 2019 |work=[[KWTV-DT]] |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://kfor.com/2019/01/29/justin-timberlakes-tour-stop-in-oklahoma-city-sets-record/ |title=Justin Timberlake\u2019s tour stop in Oklahoma City sets record |date=January 29, 2019 |work=[[KFOR-TV]] |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[StubHub]] named Timberlake the fifth-best selling live artist in the US in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2018/12/04/2018-s-best-selling-live-artists-ed-sheeran-bruce-springsteen-bts/2204203002/ |title=2018's best-selling live artists are Ed Sheeran, Bruce Springsteen and BTS, per Stubhub |last=McDermott |first=Maeve |date=December 4, 2018 |work=USA Today |accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref> According to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', ''The Man of the Woods Tour'' was the sixth-highest-grossing tour of the year, selling over 1,175,216 tickets and grossing over $149&nbsp;million in 2018.<ref name=\"gross\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2018/8488851/touring-charts-year-ed-sheeran-tops-taylor-swift-beyonce |title=The Year in Touring Charts: Ed Sheeran Claims 2018's Top Tour; Taylor Swift, Beyonc\u00e9 & Jay-Z Do Big Business |last=Eric|first=Frankenberg |date=December 5, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=December 6, 2018}}</ref> The tour received a nomination for Best Pop Tour at the 30th [[Pollstar]] Awards.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.pollstar.com/article/30th-annual-pollstar-awards-nominations-announced-136805 |title=30th Annual Pollstar Awards Nominations Announced |date=November 30, 2018 |work=Pollstar |accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring its thirteen-month run from March 2018 to April 2019, ''The Man of the Woods Tour'' sold over 1.75&nbsp;million tickets and grossed a total of over $226.3&nbsp;million from 115 shows, making it Timberlake's second most successful tour to date behind only [[The 20/20 Experience World Tour]], which grossed over $231.6&nbsp;million from 134 shows, though Timberlake's per-night basis for ''The Man of the Woods Tour'' had a higher average at $1.96&nbsp;million per-show than that of ''The 20/20 Experience World Tour'', which averaged $1.81&nbsp;million per-show.<ref name=\"2019 gross\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Man_of_the_Woods_Tour_-_Miami_-_04.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Timberlake and the Tennessee Kids performing in Miami.]] \nThe tour received generally positive reviews from critics. ''[[Toronto Star]]'' journalist Nick Krewen, who attended the opening date, gave it a score of four-out-of-four, writing \"[the] stellar tour kickoff delivers the hits and the spectacle... Even with some of the most elaborate, sophisticated visual technology available at his disposal, pop superstar Justin Timberlake managed to have his campfire moment at the Air Canada Centre Tuesday night. With a literal campfire.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Justin Timberlake\u2019s stellar tour kickoff delivers the hits and the spectacle|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/music/review/2018/03/14/justin-timberlakes-stellar-tour-kickoff-delivers-the-hits-and-the-spectacle.html|work=Toronto Star}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''{{'}}s Bob Gendron, who attended the show at the [[United Center]], praised the spectacle and said \"Parade leader. Spurned lover. Assertive dancer. Down-on-his-knees relationship savior. Bartender who handed shots out to his large ensemble. Outdoors lover who gathered around a campfire to play familiar songs. Timberlake embraced an array of roles, blurring the lines between entertainer, singer and actor.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Justin Timberlake embraces array of roles at United Center|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-ent-justin-timberlake-united-center-review-0329-story.html|work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref> Adam Graham of the ''[[Detroit News]]'' wrote it \"was an engrossing spectacle that turned the arena into his personal wooded playland; no concert artist has come close to using Little Caesars Arena\u2019s space this creatively, save for perhaps [[Lady Gaga]]. [...] Timberlake was cool and commanding, taking the stage in a jean jacket and track pants and still looking like he owned the place.\" Graham also praised Timberlake's band the Tennessee Kids, \"[they] became his own [[E Street Band]] \u2014 there were times, especially when the band turned around and played to the fans at the back of the arena, that the show recalled a [[Bruce Springsteen]] concert.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Timberlake is the \u2018Man\u2019 at Little Caesars Arena|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/opinion/columnists/adam-graham/2018/04/03/review-timberlake-man-little-caesars-arena/33500335/|work=Detroit News}}</ref>\n\nAlim Kheraj of ''[[GQ]]'', after attending the concert at London's O2 Arena, described Timberlake as \"one of the greatest live performers of all time.\" \"Timberlake and the Man of the Woods Tour has its secret weapon: captivation. With more than two decades of experience in the entertainment industry, he knows how to maintain an audience's attention, how to mould them so they\u2019re pumped at his signals and (mostly) when to take his foot off the accelerator. [...] Similarly, unlike a legacy artist, his show is still exciting, carefully crafted to bring fans the best in audio-visual technology while ensuring that, musically, things line up too.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Justin Timberlake is one of the greatest live performers of all time|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/justin-timberlake-man-of-the-woods-tour-review|work=GQ}}</ref>\n[[File:Man_of_the_Woods_Tour_-_Miami_-_03.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Timberlake on stage in Miami on May 18, 2018.]] \nFranklin Soults of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' described the first half of the show as \"ritzy glamour,\" with the \"undercut with casual outfits and attitudes that made the extravaganza feel almost relaxed, like a professional athlete\u2019s seemingly effortless performance during a career-topping late season.\" Despite describing the sing-along around the campfire as \"clumsy,\" he did believe that Timberlake won the crowd back towards the end of the show.<ref>{{cite news|title=JT steps in and out of the woods at the Garden|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2018/04/05/steps-and-out-woods-garden/tewiGgpboe4uV8idTrkIiJ/story.html|last=Soults|first=Franklin|work=Boston Globe|date=April 5, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Oakland Press]]''{{'}} Gary Graff said \"You'd be hard-pressed to find a production that makes full use of an arena in as complete a way as Timberlake is doing\" and opined \"the whole affair was tightly choreographed to appear precision at times, loose and improvisational at others. Timberlake and company were best when they were at their funkiest.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Justin Timberlake sets the Woods on fire at Little Caesars|url=http://www.theoaklandpress.com/arts-and-entertainment/20180403/review-justin-timberlake-sets-the-woods-on-fire-at-little-caesars|work=The Oakland Press}}</ref> Peter Larsen in ''[[Daily Breeze]]'' said in his review that Timberlake delivered \"with swagger and style in a terrific night at the Forum,\" and noted the opening act The Shadowboxers \"surely won over many with their energetic performance.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Justin Timberlake delivers with swagger and style in a terrific night at the Forum|url=https://www.dailybreeze.com/2018/04/29/justin-timberlake-delivers-with-swagger-and-style-in-a-terrific-night-at-the-forum/|work=Daily Breeze}}</ref>\n\nJimmie Tramel of ''[[Tulsa World]]'' said Timberlake brought \"cool factor\" to [[BOK Center]], and noted his \"appeal is such that among those spotted walking into the arena was state senator and former University of Tulsa football coach [[David Rader]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Justin Timberlake brings cool factor, fans to BOK Center for Man of the Woods tour stop|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/scene/music/justin-timberlake-brings-cool-factor-fans-to-bok-center-for/article_345febd1-735a-588e-90b7-c3fb5c133c28.html|work=Tulsa World}}</ref> Ed Masley of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' said \"there were plenty of breathtaking nature scenes projected on the scrims that dotted the arena,\" while \"it felt more like a night at the club in downtown Phoenix than a trip to Payson,\" about Timberlake he commented, \"he's only gotten better, as he proved repeatedly in the course of a heavily choreographed performance. His sense of showmanship has also gotten stronger through the years.\"<ref name=\"AZ\">{{cite news|title=Justin Timberlake 'Man of the Woods' tour brings sexy back to downtown Phoenix|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/05/03/justin-timberlake-concert-review-man-woods-tour-phoenix/552508002/|work=The Arizona Republic|author=Ed Masley|date=May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Billboard'' critics ranked ''The Man of the Woods Tour'' as one of the best live shows of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/concerts/8488754/best-concerts-2018-live-shows|title=The Best Live Shows Of 2018|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nDavid Menconi of ''[[The News & Observer]]'' said \"Justin Timberlake returns to the stage and proves why he's America's pop star\", and noted him as \"The Prince of Pop\". He also said of the show that Timberlake \"Sang quite well... But he danced even better, and that's what turned the crowd on most of all. How he moved was at least as important as how he sang.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/article223921280.html|title=Review: Justin Timberlake returns to the stage and proves why he\u2019s America\u2019s pop star|website=newsobserver}}</ref> Chris Conde of ''[[San Antonio Current]]'' deemed it \"an spectacle of undeniable talent... Even if you don\u2019t like pop music, Timberlake's show was so rich in musicianship and showmanship that anyone wanting to say something bad would be hard-pressed to, ahem, justify a negative review.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/sa-sound/archives/2019/01/20/bonfire-crackles-and-pop-justin-timberlake-literally-lights-the-atandt-center-on-fire|title=Bonfire Crackles and Pop: Justin Timberlake Lit the AT&T Center on Fire|first=Chris|last=Conde|website=San Antonio Current}}</ref>\n\n==Set list==\nThe following set list is from the show on March 13, 2018, in Toronto. It is not representative of all concerts for the duration of the tour.<ref name=\"\u2018Man of the Woods Tour\u2019 Opens\">{{cite web|last1=Bliss|first1=Karen|title=Five Highlights From Justin Timberlake's Opening Night of the Man of the Woods TourT|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8247016/justin-timberlake-man-of-the-woods-opening-night-highlights|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col}}\n#\"[[Filthy (song)|Filthy]]\"\n#\"Midnight Summer Jam\"\n#\"[[LoveStoned]]\"\n#\"[[SexyBack]]\"\n#\"[[Man of the Woods (song)|Man of the Woods]]\"\n#\"Higher Higher\"\n#\"[[Se\u00f1orita (Justin Timberlake song)|Se\u00f1orita]]\"\n#\"[[Suit & Tie]]\" {{small|(contains elements of \"[[Sly, Slick and Wicked|Sho Nuff]]\")}}\n#\"[[My Love (Justin Timberlake song)|My Love]]\" \n#\"[[Cry Me a River (Justin Timberlake song)|Cry Me a River]]\"\n#\"[[Mirrors (Justin Timberlake song)|Mirrors]]\"\n#\"[[Drink You Away]]\"\n#\"Flannel\"\n#\"[[Until the End of Time (Justin Timberlake and Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Until the End of Time]]\" \n#\"[[Dreams (Fleetwood Mac song)|Dreams]]\" / \" [[Ex-Factor]]\" / \"[[Come Together (The Beatles song)|Come Together]]\" / \"[[Thank God I'm a Country Boy]]\" {{small|(each sung by a backup singer)}}\n#\"Morning Light\"\n#\"[[What Goes Around... Comes Around]]\"\n#\"[[Say Something (Justin Timberlake song)|Say Something]]\"\n#\"Montana\"\n#\"[[Summer Love (Justin Timberlake song)|Summer Love]]\"\n#\"[[Rock Your Body]]\"\n#\"[[Supplies (song)|Supplies]]\"\n#\"[[Can't Stop the Feeling!]]\"\n{{Div col end}}\n\n;Notes:\n*On May 9, 2018, during the concert in Nashville, [[Chris Stapleton]] joined Timberlake on stage to perform \"[[Tennessee Whiskey (song)|Tennessee Whiskey]]\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/justin-timberlake-chris-stapleton-see-tennessee-whiskey-w520133 |title=See Justin Timberlake, Chris Stapleton's Nashville Reunion for 'Tennessee Whiskey' |last=McKenna |first=Brittney |date=May 10, 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n*\"[[Like I Love You]]\" was added to the set list between \"Supplies\" and \"Can't Stop the Feeling!\", while \"Flannel\" was later removed.<ref name=\"AZ\" /><ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|date=January 9, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2019|title=Concert review: How was Justin Timberlake's Charlotte show?|author=Th\u00e9oden Janes|url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/article224095115.html}}</ref>\n*On January 10, 2019, in Atlanta, [[T.I.]] joined Timberlake on stage during \"My Love\". Moreover, he performed a medley of his songs: \"[[What You Know (T.I. song)|What You Know]]\" / \"[[Bring Em Out (song)|Bring 'Em Out]]\" / \"[[Live Your Life (T.I. song)|Live Your Life]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8493169/justin-timberlake-ti-atlanta-my-love-performance-video|title=Justin Timberlake Surprises Atlanta Crowd With T.I. for 'My Love' & More: Watch|work=Billboard|author=Taylor Weatherby|date=January 11, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n*\"[[SoulMate]]\" was performed on the European leg only.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://celebmix.com/justin-timberlake-a-year-in-review/|work=CelebMix|date=January 6, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2019|author=Brittany Sims|title=Justin Timberlake: A Year in Review}}</ref>\n\n==Tour dates==<!--ALL dates must be cited. Also, please wait until Billboard Boxscore gets updated. We wait for this list to come out because it shows attendance AND gross revenue.-->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of concerts, showing date, city, country, venue, opening act, tickets sold, amount of available tickets, and gross revenue\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| City\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Venue\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Opening act\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Attendance\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Revenue\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\"| North America<ref name=\"Man of the Woods Tour Dates\"/><ref name=\"Boxscore\">Boxscore:\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|title=Current Boxscore &#124; Billboard|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 10, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411020502/https://www.billboard.com/biz/current-bo